      <file>.claude/adr/ADR-010-di-minimalism.md</file>
      <file>.claude/constraints/ai.md</file>
    </files>
    <patterns>
      <pattern>Existing AI Search index schema: read infrastructure/ai-search/ for existing index JSON files — follow the same HNSW vector profile configuration used by spaarke-rag-knowledge</pattern>
      <pattern>Existing AI Search service usage in BFF: read src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/SemanticSearch/SemanticSearchService.cs for the established pattern for querying Azure AI Search from C#</pattern>
      <pattern>Existing Azure OpenAI embedding usage: search Services/Ai/ for existing embedding generation code to reuse — do not create a second embedding client if one already exists</pattern>
      <pattern>Factory instantiation pattern (ADR-010): see SprkChatAgentFactory.cs for how tools are instantiated without DI registration</pattern>
    </patterns>
  </knowledge>

  <context>
    <background>
      SprkChat R2 introduces PlaybookDispatcher (task R2-015) which matches user natural language to the right playbook via two-stage process: (1) vector similarity search against this dedicated index, then (2) LLM refinement to extract parameters. The dedicated index is required for clean separation from the document RAG index — playbooks are ~100 short documents vs potentially 100K+ document chunks. The index is populated at playbook create/update time by PlaybookEmbeddingService (task R2-016 handles the trigger wiring; this task creates the index and the core service).

      The existing SemanticSearchService.cs provides the pattern for Azure AI Search queries in the BFF codebase. Follow that pattern exactly, adapting it for the new `playbook-embeddings` index schema.
    </background>
    <dependencies>
      No task dependencies — can start immediately in parallel with R2-001 and R2-002. Task R2-015 (PlaybookDispatcher) and R2-016 (embedding pipeline) both depend on this task completing first.
    </dependencies>
  </context>

  <steps>
    <step order="0">Read SemanticSearchService.cs and any existing AI Search index JSON files in infrastructure/ai-search/ to understand established patterns</step>
    <step order="1">Read docs/architecture/auth-AI-azure-resources.md to confirm AI Search service name, endpoint, and available OpenAI model deployments</step>
    <step order="2">Check infrastructure/ai-search/ for existing index provisioning script or CLI commands used to create indexes (e.g., Provision-AiSearchIndexes.ps1 or similar)</step>
    <step order="3">Create infrastructure/ai-search/playbook-embeddings.json with the full index schema: all fields defined in the task prompt, vector search configuration referencing text-embedding-3-large 3072-dim HNSW profile</step>
    <step order="4">Create or update the index provisioning script to create the playbook-embeddings index on spaarke-search-dev via Azure CLI (`az search index create`) or REST API</step>
    <step order="5">Execute the provisioning script to create the index in the dev environment</step>
    <step order="6">Verify the index exists: az search index show --name playbook-embeddings --service-name spaarke-search-dev --resource-group spe-infrastructure-westus2</step>
    <step order="7">Create src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/PlaybookEmbeddingService.cs implementing IndexPlaybookAsync and SearchPlaybooksAsync following the SemanticSearchService pattern</step>
    <step order="8">Create PlaybookEmbeddingDocument and PlaybookSearchResult model classes in Models/Ai/ with fields matching the index schema</step>
    <step order="9">Verify PlaybookEmbeddingService does NOT have an AddSingleton/AddScoped registration — it must be factory-instantiated. Add a comment explaining ADR-010 factory constraint.</step>
    <step order="10">Run dotnet build src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/ to verify 0 compilation errors</step>
    <step order="11">Update TASK-INDEX.md: change task R2-003 status to completed</step>
  </steps>

  <tools>
    <tool>dotnet</tool>
    <tool>git</tool>
  </tools>

  <outputs>
    <artifact type="config">infrastructure/ai-search/playbook-embeddings.json — Index schema definition with vector configuration</artifact>
    <artifact type="config">Index created on spaarke-search-dev Azure AI Search service</artifact>
    <artifact type="code">src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/PlaybookEmbeddingService.cs — IndexPlaybookAsync + SearchPlaybooksAsync</artifact>
    <artifact type="code">src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Models/Ai/PlaybookEmbeddingDocument.cs — Document model for index upload</artifact>
    <artifact type="code">src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Models/Ai/PlaybookSearchResult.cs — Search result model</artifact>
  </outputs>

  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion testable="true">az search index show --name playbook-embeddings --service-name spaarke-search-dev returns HTTP 200 with field list matching the schema</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">playbook-embeddings index has a vector field named contentVector3072 with 3072 dimensions and HNSW algorithm configuration</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">dotnet build src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/ exits with code 0</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">PlaybookEmbeddingService.cs has no AddSingleton, AddScoped, or AddTransient extension — confirmed factory-instantiated</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">PlaybookEmbeddingService.SearchPlaybooksAsync accepts a recordTypeFilter parameter and applies it as a filter expression to the AI Search query</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">PlaybookEmbeddingDocument model has all fields matching the index schema: id, playbookId, playbookName, description, triggerPhrases, recordType, entityType, tags, contentVector3072</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Index schema file committed to infrastructure/ai-search/playbook-embeddings.json</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>

  <notes>
    The DI budget constraint (ADR-010) is critical here — the BFF is already at 16 non-framework DI registrations. PlaybookEmbeddingService should follow the same instantiation pattern as other tools in SprkChatAgentFactory.cs, where services are created with `new PlaybookEmbeddingService(searchClient, embeddingClient)` rather than injected from the DI container.

    For the content composition used to generate embeddings in IndexPlaybookAsync: concatenate playbookName, description, all triggerPhrases (joined with " | "), and tags (joined with ", "). This produces a single text blob that represents the playbook's intent for embedding. Token limit for text-embedding-3-large is 8191 tokens — truncate if necessary.

    The SearchPlaybooksAsync topK parameter should default to 5 — the PlaybookDispatcher needs only the top candidates for LLM refinement.
  </notes>

